[49m[38;5;9m- 121     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Domain entity extraction.** Comprehend Medical and equivalents extract medication names, conditions, anatomy, procedures, and tests as structured entities, often with mappings to standard ontologies (RxNorm for medications, ICD-10 for conditions, SNOMED for clinical concepts). The structured entities are far more useful for downstream routing than free-text mentions; "the medication is RxNorm:104491 (lisinopril)" is unambiguous in a way that "the medication is lisinopril" is not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Domain entity extraction.** Comprehend Medical and equivalents extract medication names, conditions, anatomy, procedures, and tests as structured entities. The ontology mappings (RxNorm for medications, ICD-10-CM for conditions, SNOMED CT for clinical concepts) are particularly valuable for downstream routing, but they require separate API calls. With Comprehend Medical specifically, the base DetectEntitiesV2 call returns entity categories and traits (medication names, conditions, anatomy) without ontology codes. Linking entities to ontology codes requires additional calls: InferRxNorm (returns RxNorm concept codes for medication entities), InferICD10CM (returns ICD-10-CM codes for condition entities), and InferSNOMEDCT (returns SNOMED CT codes for clinical concept entities). The pipeline runs all four calls in parallel on the same transcript text and merges the ontology codes onto the base entities by text offset. The result is structured entities with full ontology mappings: "the medication at offset 42-52 is RxNorm:104491 (lisinopril)" is unambiguous in a way that "the medication is lisinopril" is not. Other vendors (Google Healthcare Natural Language API, Microsoft Text Analytics for Health) combine entity detection and ontology linking in a single call; the multi-call pattern is Comprehend Medical-specific.
